        <section class="info-section">
            <div class="info-container">
                <h2>Optimal Nutrition for Buffalo</h2>
                <p>Nutrition is the cornerstone of buffalo health. A balanced diet should include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Forage:</strong> High-quality hay, silage, and pasture grasses, adapted to buffalo's
                        digestive system.</li>
                    <li><strong>Concentrates:</strong> Grains and oilseeds for energy and protein supplementation, such
                        as barley and soybean meal.</li>
                    <li><strong>Supplements:</strong> Essential minerals and vitamins to prevent deficiencies and
                        maintain buffalo health.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Ensure constant access to clean water and adjust feeding based on the buffalo's life stage and
                    production level.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Environmental Needs -->
        <section class="info-section">
            <div class="info-container">
                <h2>Ideal Environmental Conditions</h2>
                <p>Buffalo thrive in environments that provide comfort and safety. Consider the following:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Climate Control:</strong> Provide adequate shelter and ventilation, especially in hot
                        and humid climates.</li>
                    <li><strong>Bedding:</strong> Use clean, dry bedding like straw or sand to keep buffalo comfortable.
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Space:</strong> Ensure adequate space for movement and reduce stress through proper
                        housing design.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Regularly clean and maintain facilities to promote a healthy living environment.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Common Diseases and Prevention -->
        <section class="info-section">
            <div class="info-container">
                <h2>Health Challenges and Disease Prevention</h2>
                <p>Preventing and managing diseases is critical for maintaining a healthy herd:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Foot and Mouth Disease (FMD):</strong> Monitor for symptoms like fever and blisters;
                        vaccinate as needed.</li>
                    <li><strong>Brucellosis:</strong> Implement strict hygiene and vaccination protocols to prevent this
                        bacterial infection.</li>
                    <li><strong>Parasite Management:</strong> Regular deworming and external parasite control are
                        essential for buffalo health.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Work closely with a veterinarian to develop a health management plan tailored to your herd.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Health Maintenance and Best Practices -->
        <section class="info-section">
            <div class="info-container">
                <h2>Maintaining Optimal Health</h2>
                <p>Keeping buffalo healthy requires consistent management practices:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Regular Check-ups:</strong> Schedule routine veterinary visits for health assessments.
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Parasite Control:</strong> Implement deworming programs and manage external parasites
                        like ticks and flies.</li>
                    <li><strong>Nutrition Management:</strong> Regularly evaluate and adjust diets to meet the changing
                        needs of your buffalo.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Maintain detailed health records for each buffalo to track treatments, vaccinations, and health
                    history.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Breeding and Reproductive Health -->
        <section class="info-section">
            <div class="info-container">
                <h2>Breeding and Reproductive Strategies</h2>
                <p>Effective breeding management leads to successful reproduction and healthy calves:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Breeding Programs:</strong> Implement a breeding program that suits your herd's needs,
                        considering both natural and artificial insemination.</li>
                    <li><strong>Pregnancy Management:</strong> Monitor pregnant buffalo closely and prepare for calving
                        by ensuring a clean, stress-free environment.</li>
                    <li><strong>Calf Care:</strong> Ensure calves receive colostrum within the first few hours of life
                        for immunity and monitor their health closely.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Consult with breeding experts to optimize reproductive success in your herd.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Market Insights and Financial Management -->
